ce:section.ce:para:
To gain more insight in PL quenching effect of NFTCDs exclusively towards NEs, MET, and DCNA, the PL quenching mechanism was systematically studied. Theoretically, PL quenching may take place via any one of the following processes: formation of non-fluorescent ground state complex, electron transfer or energy transfer. In this case, addition of analyte (NEs, MET, or DCNA) to 10NFTCDs solution caused PL quenching that occurred without any significant change in λem maxima, which preclude the possibility of quenching through ground state complex formation [46,47]. Owing to electron-deficient nature of nitro compounds, another possibility of quenching phenomenon could be attributed to the electron transfer from the CB of electron rich NFTCDs to electron deficient analytes; according to which quenching efficiencies of nitrophenols should directly correlates with the number of nitro groups present. However, the quenching sequence observed in the case of 10NFTCDs (PNP > DNP > TNP) which does not coincide with the electron deficient degree (TNP > DNP > PNP). These results suggested that the quenching of analytes (NEs, MET, and DCNA) cannot be merely explicate by electron transfer and the expected PL turn-off may be governed by the energy transfer process, which may arise either due to inner filter effect (IFE) or fluorescence resonance energy transfer (FRET). In both mechanism, IFE or FRET, the effective energy transfer between the fluorescent NFTCDs and analytes, can be quantified by the degree of overlap between energy absorption spectrum of quenching agent (analytes) and emission spectrum of the sensor (10NFTCDs) [23]. In addition, the nonlinear feature of SV plots for NEs, MET and DCNA at high concentration too suggested the existence of energy transfer mechanism during the PL quenching. In this regard, absorption spectra of different analytes and the emission spectrum of the fluorescent sensor (NFTCDs) were investigated (Fig. 10
                        ) [5]. As illustrated in Fig. 10(a), only absorption spectra of nitrophenols showed effective overlap with the emission spectrum of 10NFTCDs and the magnitude of spectral overlap followed the trend: PNP > DNP > TNP. Likewise, MET and DCNA showed maximum spectral overlap amongst others antibiotics (Fig. 10(b)) and pesticides (Fig. 10(c)), respectively. Evidently, the proportion of spectral overlap completely synchronized with the observed quenching competence of the studied quenching analytes. These results suggested that the quenching mechanism may be related to IFE or FRET, which can be further distinguished through fluorescence lifetime measurement [46]. As shown in Fig. 10(d), the average lifetime of the sensor 10NFTCD was calculated to be 4.18 ns which remained almost unchanged even in the presence of PNP (3.96 ns), DNP (4.04 ns), TNP (4.04 ns), MET (4.14 ns), or DCNA (4.07 ns). This fact excludes the probability of FRET in the quenching process, and confirmed that quenching occurred primarily via IFE mechanism [5,46,47]. Thus, the absorption of excitation/emission energy of the 10NFTCDs sensor by the discrete analytes studied credibly explained the astonishing quenching potency of NEs, MET and DCNA (Scheme 2
                        ).
